			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-style: italic">Eh, I never actually released the follow up to Chapter 1 in this series.  And even though I quit EQ over a year ago, I still do write based loosely on the lore.  So, I figured I would release the following 9 chapters of Ashen's story over the next few months.  I already have most written, just need to be reviewed and touched up.
<br />

<br />
For those that are interested (if any of you even still play), the Xican stories continued (yes, even after he died...) and are still 'in development' so to speak.  They just no longer follow EQ lore.  They're now loosely based on ShadowBane/Dark Age of Camelot.  In the future they may even have cameo's by some other, even older Brell players such as Jelen.  If I ever get off my lazy ass and contact him in game.  Anyhow, without further adieu...  Here is Chapter 3.  Chapters one and two can be found on the old Brell board.</span>
<br />

<br />
"Ashen, get up, get up!  Its today, finally!!"  came the shreaks of young Seriah, Ashenfist's youngest sister.  The sudden burden of the 10 year old girl jumping on his chest, easily stirring Ashen from his sleep.  With little concern a large arm rose up to shove the girl away and onto the floor, before he himself sprung from his lumpy bed.  Stumbling quickly around his room, Ashen gathered his armour, spear and shield and arranging them on the bed.
<br />

<br />
Now, standing before a small armament of weapons and armour was not the young Shaman boy of years passed but a young man.  Seventeen years of age now, Ashen had grown up well by Barbarian standards.  Six feet four inches tall, long auburn locks cascading across bare shoulders and chest which rippled with muscle.  And yet, he was not without grace.  Even now, as he stumbled frantically around his room, cursing under his breath.  Tossing stray peices of his father's battered armour on himself.  He had truly grown into the man his father had always hoped he would be.
<br />

<br />
Since his father's death and his meeting with Xican, Ashen had lived a quite life.  He provided for his family, in place of his father.  His older brother of 24, Drix, though blind had become a wonderous tracker and often aided Ashen in the hunt.  His younger brothers, Isindel and Urieh though only seven and ten themselves often came along for the excitement.  The family was doing well.  His three sisters were all doing well in school and his mother, though widowed for almost ten years now was living a happy life.
<br />

<br />
Today, however was a big day in the household.  Ashen was going to be officially recognised as a man after the day's events.  A ceremony which required Ashen to hunt and slay one of the largest Mammoth's in all of the EverFrost peaks.  A giant given by Mammoth stature, the locals had named it 'Trundle'.  Today Ashen would hunt alone.  Meanwhile, the rest of the family would prepare a great feast for his return.
<br />

<br />
So, kneeling at the door Ashen wrapped his tree like arms around each of his family members.  They would each bid him a good luck and offer their prayers for his safe return-  though they were taken in jest by Ashen.  And with a warm good-bye he set out toward his goal for the day.
<br />

<br />
It was perhaps mid-day when Ashen first caught a good trail of the beast.  Fresh tracks left in the snow, the likes of which Ashen thought he could still feel the pervading warmth from.  Running his fingers along the inside of the tracks, glancing up on occassion and judging his knowledge of Mammoths, he hoped he would be caught up in an hours time to the Giant, at this rate...
<br />

<br />
But, that wouldn't settle for this over-zealous Shaman.  No, Ashen rose immediately to his feet.  Muttering a few words a brief glimmer of cerulean light would surround his body, enstilling him with the spirit of the Wolf.  Bursting forward in a dead sprint, the likes of which would rival puma, Ashen sped over the slopes of the frozen wasteland, in search of Trundle.
<br />

<br />
And he did eventually find his prey.  Some twenty minutes later, Ashen found himself unfortunately face-to-face with the beast.  Who, ironically had been hunting him as well.  It was with a great alarm that Ashen saw the beast charging over a wind-swept slope of the tundra and directly toward him.
<br />

<br />
Before the boy could react quick enough, the two large ivory tusks had already been forced to either side of his body.  The solid forhead of the animal slamming fourth and hurling Ashen to the ground.  The mammoth head would rise up once more, Ashen's arms coiled around the long tusks, holding for dear life.  Three more times the beast would slam Ashen down into the snow upon his back.
<br />

<br />
The fourth time the animal began to rise, Ashen was quick to act.  A flurry of words rolling from his lips and an out-stretched palm beckoning an emerald glow which over-took Trundle's massive frame.  Disease and Poison seeping into the great beast's pores and slowly eating away at his strength from the inside.
<br />

<br />
The reaction was almost instant.  Trundle would toss his head to the side.  Tusks locked around Ashen and tossing him several meters away.  The beast attempted to turn and run, but found itself weakening to the spell of the Shaman.  Stumbling awkwardly away, it wasn't long before Ashen would be upon it.  Spear rakishly jabbing at the underbelly and legs of the beast.  Peircing and slashing random chunks of flesh astray.  Finally, the beast would topple over to one side.  And in a single fell swoop, Ashen would plunge his spear deep into the belly of the Mammoth.
<br />

<br />
Trundle had been slain and Ashen was now a man.  Carving the tusks and useable meat from the body, Ashen stowed them away in his backpack.  Leaving the rest of the carcass to the wolves and bears.  Then, with great excitement he rushed home.  The Spirit of the Wolf and his own pride carrying him faster than ever before.  Finally coming to a stop outside his home, the scent of fresh stew brewing inside had leaked out and surrounded the entire town of Halas.  Ashen breathed in the thick aroma that could only be coming from his home and there he stood with pride, looking over the modest little house.
<br />

<br />
Stepping boastfully to the door, Ashen nudged it open with a wild smile etched upon his lips.  It faded quickly...
<br />

<br />
Ashen's home was torn asunder.  The clear signs of a struggle alarmed Ashen, a deep fear creeping over him as his eyes rose from the ground to survey the entire entrance of the room.  The first sight was that of his mother, lying several feet in front of Ashen, her chest and stomach split open and entrails dangling the gaping wound.  Stuttering forward in a maelstrom of emotion, Ashen took a few steps deeper inside the home, only to find the corpses of the rest of his family, left in similar manner to his mother.
<br />

<br />
All but his older brother, Drix and youngest brother, Isindel were left in a bloody heap.  Single wounds to the throat, chest and head accompanying them all.  It wasn't until Ashen crept into his own room that he found his two brothers.  Drix was left upon the ground, several limbs broken and a limp neck, no doubt broken.  Gashes, cuts and bruises lining his entire body.  Though blind, he clearly attempted to fight back whatever had attacked them.  Finally, in horror, Ashen looked up to his wall.  Where Isindel was impaled upon a spear, embedded in the wall.  His face rent from what appeared to be nails tearing away the flesh.  The spear directly through the center of his abdomen...  The youngest brother was left to die a slow death, bleeding out in pain.
<br />

<br />
Ashen's world began to spin.  Everything was hazy and he felt ill.  Stumbling a few feet forward, he grasped for something to hold him up, only to find the limp limb of his younger brother, dangling from the wall.  Turning immediately, he was overwhelmed suddenly.  His body convulsing and twitching as he vomitted repeatedly.  Tears streaking his cheeks as he tried to reason with the situation.  Ashen fell to the floor, spasming and twitching in a pool of vomit and the blood of his family.
<br />

<br />
Several hours later, the boy came from his stupor.  And where once sadness and confusion clouded his thought, now there was anger.  Rage unbridled and the lust for vengeance.  Rising to his feet, his eyes found the spear which now impaled his brother and glancing over the haft of the weapon the mark of Martar IceBear was clear.  Ashen grimaced in pain, memories of his father's death flooding back before him.
<br />

<br />
Grabbing the spear at his back, Ashenfist took off once more into the Everfrost peaks.  Continual sobs and howls surrounding the boy as he ran.  Ran for anything, he had to escape it all.  He had to find Martar and end it all.  He wasn't a child anymore.  He was a man and no longer weak.  He would end this once and for all.  This was the reckoning.  He was the bigger man, now!
<br />

<br />
It seemed like he ran for days on end, fatigue gnawing at Ashen's body as he finally came to the entrance of BlackBurrow.  And finally, he laid eyes on his prey.  Martar IceBear.  The rage that overtook the boy was indescribable.  The sobs and sniveling faded instantly and were replaced by a battle cry, filled with anguish and rage.  In his rage, Ashen charged Martar blindly, spear in hand ready to end it all with a grueling melee battle.
<br />

<br />
Rushing head on to the larger man, Ashen thrust his spear forward aimed to impale the man as he had down to Isindel.  Yet, Martar was no fool.  The spear was knocked easily aside.  A blunt club curling up from Martar's freehand, slamming roughly into the side of Ashen's head.  A spray of crimson tainting the air, before Ashen stumbled to the side.  Trying to recover he hefted the spear up once more, stuttering around to face Marter, only to find another blunt smash of the club.  This time, slamming down on Ashen's nose.  A crackle of bone vibrating through Ashen's skull accompanied the searing pain as his knows was broken in several places.
<br />

<br />
Again, he stumbled.  This time raising the spear in defense, Martar simply reached out, grabbing the length of it and tossing it aside.  His hand extending to grab Ashen by the length of his hair, roughly slamming his head against the granite walls of Blackburrow.  The impact of bone and rock rattling throughout the whole of the peaks in a low echo.  Repeatedly, Ashen's head was slammed against the rock, pools of blood forming beneath his body and tracing over his face.
<br />

<br />
Ashen's sight had begun to blur, and black out, blood flowing through his eyes and clouding his vision.  He wasn't sure where Martar was, he could feel his footing slipping.  Dizziness.  He stumbled a few times, reaching out and trying to grasp at the wall for comfort.  Until finally, he fell to the ground.
<br />

<br />
Only seconds later the strong arm of a man hurling him back to his feet shocked Ashen back into conciousness.  Which wouldn't have lasted long, though the sudden intense pain of steel biting into his right shoulder woke him from stupor.  His own spear embedded in the right side of his chest and impailing him against the wall.  Just like his brother.  And before him, the blurred image of Martar.  Laughing at him.
<br />

<br />
"You remember me, doncha boy?  You gave me a few good bumps and bruises last we met.  Remember boy-?"  A rough slap jerked Ashen back to attention as he had begun to fade.  "You remember?  That was when I killed your father boy."  A rough thrust of Martar's fist connected with Ashen's jaw, jerking his head to the side.  "You live now, boy.  And remember this.  You will never be good enough.  You're shit beneath my boot.  Hear me boy?"  And with that, Martar drew his arm back, repeatedly slamming the full force of his forearm into Ashen's face.  Four times the sickening crash of impact filled the air.
<br />

<br />
Through the blood and dizziness, Ashen's head lifted slowly.  His gaze catching the blurred figure of Martar walking away.  Laughing.  Before everything blurred completely from vision and he faded into numbness...
<br />

<br />
